1
0:00:38,080 --> 0:00:40,640
在东南亚的遥远一隅
In a far corner of South-East Asia,

2
0:00:40,920 --> 0:00:43,440
有一片珊瑚礁三角区
lies the Coral Triangle.

3
0:00:46,880 --> 0:00:50,600
这里有世界上最丰富的珊瑚礁群落
A cluster of the richest coral reefs, in the world.

4
0:00:56,280 --> 0:01:00,040
这座海底城市生机勃勃
Undersea cities crammed full of life.

5
0:01:06,720 --> 0:01:09,160
在拥挤的大都市
As in any crowded metropolis,

6
0:01:09,600 --> 0:01:12,360
有对地盘
there is fierce rivalry for space,

7
0:01:16,720 --> 0:01:18,000
对食物
for food

8
0:01:22,840 --> 0:01:24,160
以及对伴侣的激烈争夺
and for a partner.

9
0:01:26,240 --> 0:01:30,560
但珊瑚礁也是个充满机遇的地方
But the reef is also a place full of opportunity.

10
0:01:43,760 --> 0:01:44,880
一只乌贼
A cuttlefish.

11
0:02:01,440 --> 0:02:05,480
它是捕蟹专家
It specialises in hunting crabs.

12
0:02:13,960 --> 0:02:17,280
但大体型的螃蟹是危险的猎物
But a large crab is a dangerous quarry.

13
0:02:25,240 --> 0:02:27,240
它的蟹钳力量很大
It has powerful claws.

14
0:02:31,200 --> 0:02:34,640
但这只乌贼有独门本领
The cuttlefish, however, has a remarkable talent.

15
0:02:40,480 --> 0:02:43,840
它的皮肤里有数百万色素细胞
Its skin contains millions of pigment cells

16
0:02:44,040 --> 0:02:46,520
可以创造出不断变化的色彩
with which it can create ever-changing colours

17
0:02:46,600 --> 0:02:47,880
和图案
and patterns.

18
0:02:57,280 --> 0:03:01,160
这样的色彩明显迷惑了螃蟹
And that apparently hypnotises the crab.

19
0:03:23,440 --> 0:03:25,040
乌贼可能很聪明
A cuttlefish may be clever,

20
0:03:25,600 --> 0:03:27,160
但鲨鱼更庞大
but a shark is bigger.

21
0:03:29,920 --> 0:03:31,880
它能吞掉乌贼
And it eats cuttlefish.

22
0:03:34,720 --> 0:03:36,200
该走了
Time to disappear.

23
0:03:52,400 --> 0:03:53,840
继续捕猎
Back to the hunt.

24
0:03:56,920 --> 0:04:00,840
不一样的目标 但一样迷惑人的手段
A new target, but the same mesmerising technique.

25
0:04:16,840 --> 0:04:21,240
这些能在拥挤的海底城市中
For those that manage to establish themselves in these bustling

26
0:04:21,360 --> 0:04:22,720
有立足之地的生命
undersea cities,

27
0:04:22,960 --> 0:04:25,520
都能得到丰厚的回报
there can be great rewards.

28
0:04:45,640 --> 0:04:48,920
珊瑚虫在热带海洋温暖 清澈的浅海域
Corals build themselves homes of limestone,

29
0:04:49,080 --> 0:04:52,280
为自己建造石灰岩家园
in the warm, clear, shallow seas of the Tropics.

30
0:04:56,360 --> 0:04:58,920
珊瑚礁覆盖了海床
Their reefs occupy less than one tenth

31
0:04:59,040 --> 0:05:02,000
不到千分之一的地方
of one percent of the ocean floor.

32
0:05:05,840 --> 0:05:08,240
然而 它们却是我们已知的
Yet, they're home to a quarter

33
0:05:08,400 --> 0:05:10,720
四分之一海洋生物的家园
of all known marine species.

34
0:05:15,280 --> 0:05:16,760
珊瑚礁结构复杂
They are complex,

35
0:05:17,160 --> 0:05:19,480
有无穷尽的不同结构
infinitely variant structures,

36
0:05:20,400 --> 0:05:23,920
为它们的居民提供各式各样的住所
providing all kinds of homes for their many residents,

37
0:05:27,040 --> 0:05:28,520
有顶层豪华套房
from penthouse suites,

38
0:05:30,400 --> 0:05:32,200
也有隐蔽的洞穴
to backstreet dens.

39
0:05:38,200 --> 0:05:40,920
在澳大利亚的大堡礁上
Here, on Australia's Great Barrier Reef,

40
0:05:41,560 --> 0:05:45,280
珊瑚石斑鱼以捕猎小鱼为生
a coral grouper lives by hunting for small fish.

41
0:05:51,040 --> 0:05:52,800
但如果你挤不进狭小的裂缝里
But how do you get a meal here,

42
0:05:54,000 --> 0:05:56,720
要怎么吃到自己的美餐呢
when you're too big to squeeze into crevices?

43
0:06:05,560 --> 0:06:08,800
珊瑚石斑鱼也有对手
And the grouper also has a rival,

44
0:06:13,200 --> 0:06:15,360
对方智商极高
one which is highly intelligent,

45
0:06:20,160 --> 0:06:22,280
也捕捉同样的猎物
and seeks the same kind of prey.

46
0:06:25,200 --> 0:06:26,320
一只章鱼
An octopus.

47
0:06:47,560 --> 0:06:51,400
它可以伸进极其狭窄的裂缝
It can reach into really narrow cracks.

48
0:06:59,800 --> 0:07:01,080
即使如此
Even so,

49
0:07:01,560 --> 0:07:03,240
它的猎物也常常会逃脱
its prey often escapes.

50
0:07:15,160 --> 0:07:17,160
如果它们合作呢
What if they could work together?

51
0:07:33,360 --> 0:07:35,480
石斑鱼会变得苍白
The grouper turns pale,

52
0:07:39,720 --> 0:07:42,920
努力吸引章鱼的注意
and tries to attract the octopus's attention.

53
0:07:48,400 --> 0:07:50,080
它在表演倒立
It performs a head stand.

54
0:07:56,960 --> 0:08:00,000
石斑鱼不仅是在向章鱼打暗号
Not only is the grouper signalling to the octopus,

55
0:08:00,360 --> 0:08:03,200
也在说明猎物的藏身之处
it's indicating where the prey is hiding.

56
0:08:16,480 --> 0:08:18,720
章鱼伸入触手
The octopus reaches inside.

57
0:08:22,440 --> 0:08:23,960
鱼受到惊吓
The fish take fright.

58
0:08:27,680 --> 0:08:31,760
直接游进了石斑鱼的嘴里
And swim straight into the grouper's jaws.

59
0:08:39,440 --> 0:08:42,000
有时候 章鱼享受到回报
Sometimes, the octopus gets the reward,

60
0:08:43,480 --> 0:08:46,080
有时候 是石斑鱼
sometimes, the grouper does.

61
0:08:51,640 --> 0:08:53,720
这两种截然不同的生物
Two very different species

62
0:08:53,920 --> 0:08:57,600
知道在珊瑚城里团队合作
have discovered that teamwork can bring success,

63
0:08:57,800 --> 0:08:59,800
可以带来成功
in reef city.

64
0:09:16,240 --> 0:09:19,760
实际上 团队合作是珊瑚礁生活的
Teamwork , in fact, is the very foundation of life

65
0:09:19,920 --> 0:09:21,040
根本基础
on the reef.

66
0:09:28,880 --> 0:09:32,840
珊瑚虫本身也是依靠合作关系生存
The corals themselves also rely on a partnership.

67
0:09:34,240 --> 0:09:37,480
一种更为亲密的关系
But one of a much more intimate kind.

68
0:09:46,040 --> 0:09:49,520
珊瑚虫和海葵一样都属于腔肠动物
Corals are colonies of anemone-like animals,

69
0:09:49,880 --> 0:09:51,000
水螅体
polyps.

70
0:09:51,880 --> 0:09:54,760
有一些水螅和砂粒一样小
Some as small as grains of sand.

71
0:09:57,600 --> 0:10:00,320
在水螅组织里
Living inside the tissues of each polyp,

72
0:10:00,800 --> 0:10:05,640
住着肉眼不可见的微小共生藻类
are minute plant-like cells, invisible to the naked eye.

73
0:10:11,160 --> 0:10:14,040
这些共生藻类
By day flourishing in tropical sunshine,

74
0:10:14,400 --> 0:10:16,960
白天在热带阳光里欣欣向荣
the plant-like cells provide the polyps

75
0:10:17,080 --> 0:10:19,880
提供了水螅高达90%的食物
with up to 90% of their food.

76
0:10:32,760 --> 0:10:36,200
天黑的时候 水螅继续
And when it's dark, the polyps continue to feed

77
0:10:36,520 --> 0:10:41,880
依靠触角来捕捉漂浮的可食用颗粒
by using their tentacles to grab edible particles drifting by.

78
0:10:49,760 --> 0:10:53,480
水螅也会从海水里提取碳酸钙
The polyps also extract calcium carbonate from the sea water,

79
0:10:53,720 --> 0:10:57,520
来搭建自己的石头房子
and use it to build a stony housing for themselves.

80
0:11:00,600 --> 0:11:04,120
珊瑚群落会持续生长数百年
Coral colonies can continue to grow for centuries.

81
0:11:04,840 --> 0:11:06,320
甚至可能一千年
Possibly millennia.

82
0:11:10,040 --> 0:11:14,560
它们能造出人类住宅那么大的结构体
And they can build structures that can reach the size of a house.

83
0:11:29,680 --> 0:11:33,040
最大的海底城市 是大堡礁
The biggest of their cities，is the Great Barrier Reef.

84
0:11:34,520 --> 0:11:40,320
它遍及澳大利亚东北部沿岸1400英里
It runs for over 1400 miles along the coast of North East Australia.

85
0:11:51,720 --> 0:11:56,080
珊瑚礁的内部活动不管在哪里都不会完全停止
Activity in coral reefs, wherever they are, never ceases.

86
0:11:58,360 --> 0:12:00,800
拂晓时分 白天的工作开始了
At dawn, the day shift begins.

87
0:12:01,800 --> 0:12:06,200
伴随着鱼 虾 和其他栖息在珊瑚礁上的生物
Accompanied by a chorus of submarine song,

88
0:12:06,600 --> 0:12:10,840
共同奏响海底之歌
created by fish, shrimps, and other inhabitants of the reef.

89
0:12:24,920 --> 0:12:27,960
这座城市的每位居民都有自己的角色
Every resident in this city, has its role.

90
0:12:28,920 --> 0:12:31,160
食腐动物 像海参
Scavengers, like the sea cucumber,

91
0:12:31,360 --> 0:12:33,280
回收其他生物的排泄物
recycle the waste of others.

92
0:12:35,960 --> 0:12:38,640
这些鹦嘴鱼会咬下大块的珊瑚
These parrot fish, bite off chunks of coral

93
0:12:38,720 --> 0:12:42,080
咬碎它 吸收其中的养分
and crunch it to extract the contents.

94
0:12:54,440 --> 0:12:57,240
其余物质的就被排出去 成为沙粒
And then, excrete the rest as sand.

95
0:13:13,120 --> 0:13:15,760
婆罗洲的绿海龟
Green turtles, here in Borneo,

96
0:13:15,960 --> 0:13:19,840
会定期造访固定的某块珊瑚
pay regular visits to a particular patch of coral.

97
0:13:25,240 --> 0:13:29,960
这个小女孩起得很早 领先了其他海龟
This little female is up early and one step ahead of the others.

98
0:13:49,360 --> 0:13:53,720
海龟要沿着珊瑚礁游很远才能到达这里
Turtles travel long distances along the reef in order to get here.

99
0:13:57,400 --> 0:13:59,560
这就是它们的目的地
This is their destination.

100
0:14:00,080 --> 0:14:01,520
海龟岩
Turtle Rock.

101
0:14:08,120 --> 0:14:12,560
数代来此的海龟在它的顶端磨出了凹槽
Generations of visiting turtles have worn a hollow in its top.

102
0:14:26,000 --> 0:14:28,680
这是鲇鱼
This is home to blennies

103
0:14:29,760 --> 0:14:31,360
还有刺尾鱼的家园
and surgeon fish.

104
0:14:32,840 --> 0:14:39,500
它们会清理海龟身上的藻类 寄生虫和死皮
They clean the visitors picking off any algae, parasites and dead skin,that they can find.

105
0:14:43,880 --> 0:14:46,680
其他顾客也快到了
Other client are close behind.

106
0:14:54,520 --> 0:14:56,480
大家在排队等候
A queue is forming.

107
0:15:13,000 --> 0:15:15,560
一只成年雄性海龟挡住了它们的去路
The big males barge their way in.

108
0:15:31,160 --> 0:15:34,640
较小只的雌性海龟被迫离开
And the smaller female is forced out.

109
0:15:43,360 --> 0:15:46,000
其他海龟还在争执的时候
She takes a quick turn around the block,

110
0:15:51,210 --> 0:15:53,400
她迅速在石块周围绕了一圈
while the others are squabbling.

111
0:16:06,320 --> 0:16:08,640
然后 偷偷溜了回来
And then, she sneaks back in.

112
0:16:20,440 --> 0:16:23,240
清理者饱餐了一顿
So the cleaners get a nutritious meal,

113
0:16:23,880 --> 0:16:28,280
它们的顾客则除去了身上的污垢和寄生虫
and their customers are freed of their parasites and other encumbrances.

114
0:16:33,600 --> 0:16:38,280
如今 在清洗站得到的悉心呵护
And it's now thought, that a spot of pampering at a cleaning station

115
0:16:38,400 --> 0:16:40,360
甚至被认为有减缓压力的作用
may even reduce stress.

116
0:16:56,360 --> 0:16:59,760
中东地区的陆地十分炎热干燥
The lands of the Middle East are so hot and dry,

117
0:16:59,860 --> 0:17:02,700
大部分地表都毫无生机
that much of their surface is almost lifeless.

118
0:17:04,600 --> 0:17:06,860
但是在红海
But here in the Red Sea,

119
0:17:07,200 --> 0:17:09,420
珊瑚礁生机勃勃
Coral Reefs flourish wonderfully.

120
0:17:12,600 --> 0:17:14,160
海岸边的海水
The waters offshore,

121
0:17:14,240 --> 0:17:17,120
有几乎和热带雨林一样丰富的物种
are almost as rich in life as a rainforest.

122
0:17:20,180 --> 0:17:22,620
有的动物来珊瑚礁
And some animals come to the reefs

123
0:17:22,880 --> 0:17:25,800
就是为了休息和放松
simply for rest and relaxation.

124
0:17:45,240 --> 0:17:48,240
宽吻海豚一家
The family of bottlenose dolphins

125
0:17:48,300 --> 0:17:49,930
整晚都在近海捕食
are resting on the reef

126
0:17:50,040 --> 0:17:52,440
正在这里休息
after a night's feeding offshore.

127
0:18:12,640 --> 0:18:15,360
成年海豚和它们的宝宝睡着之后
Whilst the adult and their babies sleep,

128
0:18:17,200 --> 0:18:20,350
这些正值青少年的海豚则出发探索海洋
the adolescents set off to explore...

129
0:18:24,260 --> 0:18:26,780
它们似乎正在做游戏
...and they appear to make up games.

130
0:18:36,100 --> 0:18:38,940
这个游戏可以叫做 接珊瑚
You might call this one,"Catch the coral."

131
0:18:45,020 --> 0:18:47,220
游戏规则不很清楚
The rules aren't entirely clear.

132
0:19:04,140 --> 0:19:06,780
它们捡起折断的珊瑚
They pick up different bits of broken coral,

133
0:19:09,740 --> 0:19:10,980
然后扔下去
and drop them.

134
0:19:13,220 --> 0:19:15,500
有的沉得很快
Some fall fast.

135
0:19:18,590 --> 0:19:20,760
有的慢一些
Others sink more slowly.

136
0:19:38,260 --> 0:19:40,840
有的珊瑚礁沉下去的样子
And some seem to be descending in a way

137
0:19:40,900 --> 0:19:42,880
把大家都逗乐了
that pleases everybody.

138
0:19:57,720 --> 0:20:03,100
只有最成功的海洋居民才能享受玩游戏的奢侈时光
Only the most successful city residents can afford the luxury of playing games.

139
0:20:05,780 --> 0:20:08,420
但是 这些游戏是有价值的
But, such games do that their value.

140
0:20:08,650 --> 0:20:12,540
玩游戏能让年轻的海豚增强身体的协调性和敏捷度
They may help the youngsters develop the coordination and the agility

141
0:20:12,660 --> 0:20:16,500
它们需要这些素质 将来才能在广阔的海域捕食
that they will need when they start hunting in the open sea.

142
0:20:28,300 --> 0:20:31,580
每片珊瑚礁都有明显的边界
Every reef has a sharply defined boundary.

143
0:20:34,260 --> 0:20:36,060
这是海底城市的城墙
Its city walls.

144
0:20:41,300 --> 0:20:44,340
另一面则是海底断层
On the outer side is the drop off.

145
0:20:45,380 --> 0:20:48,940
城墙阻挡海浪侵袭城市
These ramparts protect the city from the ocean waves.

146
0:20:52,970 --> 0:20:56,780
但每天会被潮水淹没两次
But twice a day, the walls are covered by the incoming tide.

147
0:21:06,860 --> 0:21:11,740
在巴哈马群岛 海水的冲击创造了一个奇特的现象
In the Bahamas, the rush of the water creates a truly strange phenomenon.

148
0:21:23,340 --> 0:21:27,140
过去 水手中流传着一个海洋巨怪的传说
Seamen once told tales of a giant sea monster,

149
0:21:27,300 --> 0:21:29,700
它蛰伏在珊瑚礁的深处
lurking here deep inside the reef,

150
0:21:30,460 --> 0:21:33,180
能将水手们拖进无尽的深渊
that would drag sailors to their doom.

151
0:21:51,420 --> 0:21:56,980
今天 我们知道这只不过是潮水
Today, we know it is in fact a whirlpool created by the incoming tide

152
0:21:57,100 --> 0:21:59,540
冲击深处的珊瑚礁所产生的漩涡
rushing over deep coral caves.

153
0:22:05,340 --> 0:22:09,820
这些水流从开阔海面为珊瑚礁带来了
These currents bring in fresh supplies  of microscopic food to the reef

154
0:22:09,980 --> 0:22:11,380
新鲜的微生物补给
from the open ocean.

155
0:22:14,820 --> 0:22:18,100
在马尔代夫 在大潮来临时
And in the Maldives, on the biggest tides,

156
0:22:18,420 --> 0:22:20,740
其中的一片潟湖
one particular coral lagoon

157
0:22:20,940 --> 0:22:23,340
聚集着大量的浮游生物
become so flooded with plankton,

158
0:22:25,140 --> 0:22:28,660
吸引了上百头海洋巨人的到来
that it attracts hundreds of ocean giants.

159
0:22:31,380 --> 0:22:33,140
它们就是蝠鲼
Manta Rays.

160
0:22:34,980 --> 0:22:37,220
翼展可达3米
With three meter wing spans.

161
0:22:46,740 --> 0:22:49,660
宽大的头鳍像是张开的巨口
With their huge sloth like mouths wide open

162
0:22:51,500 --> 0:22:53,540
滤食浮游生物
they filter out the plankton.

163
0:23:02,820 --> 0:23:06,260
蝠鲼们随后创造出一个漩涡
And the mantas create a vortex of their own

164
0:23:06,700 --> 0:23:08,980
来集中它们的食物
that further concentrates their food.

165
0:23:51,820 --> 0:23:56,380
这种行为被称作蝠鲼旋风
This behaviour has been called the manta cyclone.

166
0:24:07,060 --> 0:24:09,180
然后潮水退去
Then the tide changes,

167
0:24:10,020 --> 0:24:12,020
食物来源断了
and the supply of food is cut of.

168
0:24:15,740 --> 0:24:18,180
蝠鲼们便离开了潟湖
The mantas leave the lagoon.

169
0:24:27,740 --> 0:24:32,380
有珊瑚礁庇护的内部生活十分安静祥和
Life on the sheltered side of the reef is tranquil and peaceful.

170
0:24:37,460 --> 0:24:40,700
在这些郊区 任何想要逃离
In these suburbs,any creature wishing to escape

171
0:24:40,700 --> 0:24:43,340
珊瑚城熙攘生活的生物
from the bustling crowds of reef city,

172
0:24:44,860 --> 0:24:46,460
都能找到栖身之所
can find plenty of space.

173
0:24:50,180 --> 0:24:51,300
不过
On the other hand,

174
0:24:51,460 --> 0:24:53,420
这里也无处可藏
there is nowhere to hide.

175
0:25:01,380 --> 0:25:02,580
这让夜晚的珊瑚礁
That, at night,

176
0:25:03,060 --> 0:25:05,020
变得危机四伏
makes it a dangerous place.

177
0:25:11,740 --> 0:25:15,100
夜间的捕食者 就像这只狮子鱼
Nocturnal predators,such as this lion fish,

178
0:25:15,740 --> 0:25:17,700
巡视着珊瑚礁的边缘地带
patrol the reef edge.

179
0:25:48,660 --> 0:25:51,700
猎人变成了猎物
The hunter has become the hunted.

180
0:26:10,820 --> 0:26:12,020
一只博比特虫
A bobbit,

181
0:26:14,430 --> 0:26:16,540
一种巨型肉食性蠕虫
a giant carnivorous worm

182
0:26:17,180 --> 0:26:19,340
有像匕首一样锋利的颚
with jaws as sharp as daggers.

183
0:26:23,540 --> 0:26:28,220
它的祖先能够追溯到四亿年前
It has an ancestry that stretches back more than four hundred million years.

184
0:26:36,100 --> 0:26:38,060
体长一米
It's a meter long.

185
0:26:59,210 --> 0:27:01,660
靠味道追踪猎物
It tastes for scent.

186
0:27:08,140 --> 0:27:10,580
借水流感知动作
And feels for movement.

187
0:27:55,300 --> 0:28:00,100
黎明的光线 让珊瑚礁成为了一个安全的地方
Dawn, and with light,the reef becomes a safer place.

188
0:28:03,160 --> 0:28:05,680
小海鲷返回觅食
Little bream return to foraging.

189
0:28:15,220 --> 0:28:17,300
博比特虫似乎还没吃饱
The bobbit might still be hungry.

190
0:28:20,100 --> 0:28:23,660
但在日光下 形势已经变了
But now in daylight,the odds have shifted.

191
0:28:26,820 --> 0:28:29,060
海鲷鱼看得到博比特虫
The bream can see the bobbit.

192
0:28:33,900 --> 0:28:35,660
它们没有逃走
Instead of retreating,

193
0:28:36,300 --> 0:28:40,660
而是合力把盖在博比特虫上面的沙子吹走
they join together to blow away the sand covering the worm.

194
0:28:46,460 --> 0:28:50,580
夺走它出其不意的优势
So, taking away its advantage of surprise.

195
0:28:56,140 --> 0:28:58,580
暴露了博比特虫的藏身之所
By revealing the bobbit's hiding place,

196
0:28:58,820 --> 0:29:01,260
它们也能够更安全地捕食
they will all be able to feed more safely.

197
0:29:05,300 --> 0:29:07,300
但要真正记住这有只博比特虫
But it pays to remember

198
0:29:16,820 --> 0:29:18,540
需要付出血的代价
there is a bobbit about.

199
0:29:31,100 --> 0:29:33,180
远处的平坦沙地上
Out here, on the sand flats,

200
0:29:33,420 --> 0:29:36,260
有些动物找到了安全的栖息地
there is safe accommodation for some.

201
0:29:45,500 --> 0:29:50,860
鞍背小丑鱼一家找到了绝好的房子
The family of saddleback clownfish have found an excellent home.

202
0:29:53,580 --> 0:29:57,140
地毯海葵触手有剧毒
The tentacles of this carpet anemone can kill.

203
0:29:59,900 --> 0:30:02,500
但是小丑鱼对毒素免疫
But the clownfish are immune to the poison,

204
0:30:08,860 --> 0:30:10,860
它们把剧毒当成了保护伞
so they can shelter from danger.

205
0:30:15,820 --> 0:30:20,220
作为回报 它们使海葵免受食物残渣的困扰
In return, the fish keep the anemone clean of debris.

206
0:30:25,060 --> 0:30:26,660
所有的小丑鱼家庭
As with all clownfish,

207
0:30:26,740 --> 0:30:29,940
总是由一只大雌鱼领导
the family is ruled by a big female.

208
0:30:31,900 --> 0:30:35,460
白色的面部是领导者的象征
Her white face marks her out as the boss.

209
0:30:40,660 --> 0:30:43,340
小型的雄性必须要证明自己的价值
The diminutive male has to prove his worth,

210
0:30:43,980 --> 0:30:46,020
所以他不辞辛劳地工作
so he works tirelessly,

211
0:30:46,420 --> 0:30:50,140
移除残渣 做好所有家务活
removing debris and generally keeping on top of the housework.

212
0:31:11,500 --> 0:31:13,040
他最大的挑战
His greatest challenge

213
0:31:13,080 --> 0:31:17,860
就是为女王找到安全的产卵之所
is to find a safe place where the boss can lay her eggs.

214
0:31:21,180 --> 0:31:24,580
但附近没有固体表面 能让雌鱼在上面产卵
But there's nothing solid here for the female to lay them on.

215
0:31:30,780 --> 0:31:32,940
近处的贝壳或许能够解决问题
A nearby shell could be the solution.

216
0:31:43,940 --> 0:31:47,860
只要他能够将贝壳移到海葵的保护伞之下
If only he can move it to the protection of the anemone.

217
0:31:55,860 --> 0:31:56,980
太重了
Too heavy.

218
0:32:01,220 --> 0:32:03,700
再说 这个贝壳已经有主了
Besides, it has a mind of its own.

219
0:32:07,820 --> 0:32:08,980
寄居蟹
The hermit crab.

220
0:32:18,100 --> 0:32:20,300
但一天之中有两次
But out here, twice a day,

221
0:32:21,220 --> 0:32:24,180
潮水会为海葵做保洁工作
the anemone is swept by tidal currents,

222
0:32:24,380 --> 0:32:26,540
这也带来了新的机遇
and they bring in new opportunities.

223
0:32:29,620 --> 0:32:31,460
旧塑料瓶
An old plastic bottle.

224
0:32:35,980 --> 0:32:37,340
或许 这个可以
Perhaps, this will do.

225
0:32:45,300 --> 0:32:46,620
太轻了
Not heavy enough.

226
0:32:59,100 --> 0:33:00,380
一片椰壳
A coconut shell.

227
0:33:05,840 --> 0:33:07,740
看起来正合适
It looks just right.

228
0:33:08,580 --> 0:33:10,940
但离家太远了
But it's a long way from home.

229
0:33:29,500 --> 0:33:32,620
他无法独力搬运
And he can't move it by himself.

230
0:33:44,340 --> 0:33:47,200
所以他们齐心协力
So the pair now work together.

231
0:34:28,540 --> 0:34:31,520
稍稍调整海葵的触手
A little adjustment to the anemone's tentacles,

232
0:34:31,540 --> 0:34:33,440
给椰壳腾出位置
in order to clear a space for it.

233
0:34:36,420 --> 0:34:38,500
椰壳就固定好了
And the shell is tucked in.

234
0:34:43,870 --> 0:34:45,720
雌鱼产下卵
The female lays.

235
0:34:46,300 --> 0:34:48,800
终于有个安全的育儿房了
A safe nursery at last.

236
0:35:04,740 --> 0:35:08,400
他证明了自己有做她孩子父亲的能力
He has proved himself worthy to father her young.

237
0:35:08,900 --> 0:35:10,600
给这些卵体外授精
And he fertilizes them.

238
0:35:14,980 --> 0:35:18,400
雄鱼会小心翼翼地照料鱼卵
Now he will meticulously tend the eggs,

239
0:35:26,000 --> 0:35:31,580
在十天的孵化期内 保持它们的清洁和健康
keeping them clean and healthy until they hatch in 10 days time.

240
0:35:45,680 --> 0:35:50,880
珊瑚礁生物会竭尽全力让后代活下来
Reef creatures go to great lengths to give their young a head start in life.

241
0:35:59,940 --> 0:36:01,620
世界上最偏远的珊瑚礁
And nowhere more so

242
0:36:01,860 --> 0:36:05,140
莫过于此处了
than on the remotest reefs in the world.

243
0:36:07,580 --> 0:36:09,220
法属波利尼西亚
French Polynesia,

244
0:36:09,620 --> 0:36:12,420
位于南太平洋的中心地带
the very heart of the South Pacific.

245
0:36:19,040 --> 0:36:21,080
这里与世隔绝
Protected by their isolation,

246
0:36:21,220 --> 0:36:24,880
一些珊瑚礁还处于原始状态
some of the reefs here, are still virtually pristine.

247
0:36:34,660 --> 0:36:39,680
这条褐点石斑鱼无惊无险地长大成年了
This marbled grouper has made it in the city and reached adulthood.

248
0:36:41,020 --> 0:36:43,560
是时候繁衍后代了
Now, it's the time to mate.

249
0:36:45,460 --> 0:36:50,980
为了寻找伴侣 他必须前往珊瑚礁最凶险的区域
To find a partner, he must head to the most dangerous part of this reef:

250
0:36:52,180 --> 0:36:53,220
海底断层
The drop off.

251
0:36:58,500 --> 0:37:01,720
黑尾真鲨在此巡游
Patrolled by grey reef sharks,

252
0:37:04,640 --> 0:37:05,900
数量多达上百条
hundreds of them.

253
0:37:12,840 --> 0:37:14,480
它们看似
They seem to be resting,

254
0:37:17,380 --> 0:37:18,500
正在休息
for now.

255
0:37:28,800 --> 0:37:33,320
上千条褐点石斑鱼聚集在海床上
Thousands of other groupers have gathered on the seabed below.

256
0:37:49,640 --> 0:37:53,120
雌鱼腹部充满了大量鱼卵 正待产卵
The females are almost bursting with eggs.

257
0:37:57,900 --> 0:37:59,320
但若想成功交配
But to mate with one,

258
0:38:00,540 --> 0:38:04,240
他必须先击败其他同样在等候的雄鱼
he must first get through the crowd of other waiting males.

259
0:38:06,260 --> 0:38:09,800
其他雄鱼同样也有交配欲望
And they all have the same thing on their minds.

260
0:38:16,980 --> 0:38:20,760
它们争夺靠近雌鱼的绝佳机会
They jostle to get as close as possible to a female.

261
0:38:48,380 --> 0:38:51,260
这条雄鱼似乎已经抢占先机
This male may have secured pole position,

262
0:38:52,300 --> 0:38:55,660
但除非天时地利人和
but the female won't release her eggs for him to fertilize,

263
0:38:56,260 --> 0:38:58,620
否则雌鱼不会产卵让雄鱼授精
until conditions are just right.

264
0:39:11,100 --> 0:39:13,940
鲨鱼群开始逼近
Now the sharks begin to close in,

265
0:39:14,700 --> 0:39:18,440
关键时刻即将到来
sensing that the critical moment is approaching.

266
0:39:45,140 --> 0:39:47,700
潮水开始转向
The tide is beginning to turn.

267
0:39:50,660 --> 0:39:53,220
这或许是产卵的绝佳时机
This could be the moment to spawn.

268
0:40:00,960 --> 0:40:04,860
雌鱼突然冲向海面
Suddenly, the females rush up towards the surface

269
0:40:04,980 --> 0:40:07,580
同时释出成团的鱼卵
releasing their clouds of eggs as they go.

270
0:40:09,620 --> 0:40:13,580
雄鱼在后追逐 同时释放精子
The males pursue them, simultaneously releasing their sperm.

271
0:40:29,620 --> 0:40:33,160
石斑鱼看来准备背水一战了
It's an act the groupers seem prepared to die for.

272
0:40:37,340 --> 0:40:40,380
成败在此一举
It's now or never.

273
0:41:28,100 --> 0:41:29,580
受精的鱼卵
The fertilized eggs,

274
0:41:29,940 --> 0:41:31,460
会被水流冲散
will now be swept away

275
0:41:32,260 --> 0:41:36,020
远离其他饥饿的珊瑚礁生物
from the many hungry mouths of the reef dwellers.

276
0:41:47,740 --> 0:41:51,020
海中如云雾般的上万亿鱼卵
Most of the billions of eggs that cloud the sea,

277
0:41:51,260 --> 0:41:52,540
大多数会被吃掉
will be eaten.

278
0:41:54,620 --> 0:41:55,820
但有少数
But a few,

279
0:41:55,940 --> 0:41:58,100
却极其重要的那些鱼卵
a tiny but crucial minority,

280
0:41:58,900 --> 0:42:00,740
会找到另一处珊瑚礁
will find another reef

281
0:42:01,380 --> 0:42:02,980
在那安家落户
and make it their home.

282
0:42:16,680 --> 0:42:20,820
目前 珊瑚礁正面临新的危机
But today's coral reefs are facing a new threat.

283
0:42:25,820 --> 0:42:27,900
海水在变暖
The seas are warming.

284
0:42:31,580 --> 0:42:34,340
过去的短短数周 海水的温度
A rise in temperature of just one for two degrees

285
0:42:34,820 --> 0:42:36,300
升高了一至二摄氏度
for just a few weeks,

286
0:42:36,940 --> 0:42:42,580
看似不多 但已足以导致珊瑚虫失去身上的共生藻类
can be enough to cause the coral polyps to eject their plant-like cells.

287
0:42:50,420 --> 0:42:54,380
此时 珊瑚会失去美丽的颜色
When that happens, the corals lose both their colour,

288
0:42:54,900 --> 0:42:57,180
以及主要的食物来源
and their main source of food.

289
0:43:04,540 --> 0:43:07,020
如果高温持续
If the high temperatures are sustained,

290
0:43:07,820 --> 0:43:10,140
这样白化的珊瑚
coral, bleached in this way,

291
0:43:10,540 --> 0:43:12,140
会濒临死亡
is likely to die.

292
0:43:18,540 --> 0:43:22,860
近年来 世界上近半数的珊瑚礁
In recent years, it's thought that half the world's coral reefs,

293
0:43:23,140 --> 0:43:24,980
已受到了白化影响
have been affected by bleaching.

294
0:43:32,180 --> 0:43:35,020
其中包括澳大利亚的大堡礁
Including, since 2016,

295
0:43:35,260 --> 0:43:38,540
自2016年起计 约三分之二的浅水珊瑚
around two thirds of the shallow water corals,

296
0:43:38,700 --> 0:43:41,140
出现白化现象
on Australia's Great Barrier Reef.

297
0:43:53,860 --> 0:43:56,940
这些曾经热闹繁华的海底城市
These once crowded submarine cities,

298
0:43:58,900 --> 0:44:00,060
如今只剩
are reduced

299
0:44:00,620 --> 0:44:02,100
苍白的废墟
to bleak ruins.

300
0:44:04,500 --> 0:44:07,860
曾经的居民无家可归
and many of their inhabitants, left homeless.

301
0:44:22,740 --> 0:44:26,660
科学家预测 直至本世纪末
Some scientists predict that by the end of the century,

302
0:44:28,020 --> 0:44:30,140
目前已知的珊瑚礁群
coral reef cities as we know them,

303
0:44:31,060 --> 0:44:33,180
或将成为历史
could be a thing of the past.

304
0:44:49,660 --> 0:44:54,540
这些无价的海洋宝藏还有未来吗
Is there any future for these most precious of ocean treasures?

305
0:45:03,100 --> 0:45:07,660
这取决于海水变暖的速度
Well, that ultimately depends on how fast they heat up,

306
0:45:07,940 --> 0:45:10,180
以及程度
and how warm the seas become.

307
0:45:14,260 --> 0:45:16,020
但由于珊瑚独特的繁殖方式
And there is a glimmer of hope,

308
0:45:16,420 --> 0:45:20,220
还有一线希望
because of the way the corals reproduce themselves.

309
0:45:26,900 --> 0:45:29,140
一年中有一个特别的夜晚
On one special night of the year,

310
0:45:29,900 --> 0:45:33,780
满月会触发奇特的一幕
the full moon triggers an extraordinary event:

311
0:45:51,780 --> 0:45:54,340
珊瑚产卵
The spawning of the coral.

312
0:46:03,700 --> 0:46:08,180
所有的珊瑚礁惊人地同步产卵
With extraordinary synchrony, entire reefs reproduce.

313
0:46:24,380 --> 0:46:27,300
数十亿的受精卵
Billions of fertilized eggs drift away

314
0:46:30,340 --> 0:46:32,580
随着洋流漂散
carried by the ocean currents.

315
0:46:39,060 --> 0:46:42,340
除了珊瑚
And it's not just the corals that spawn,

316
0:46:44,260 --> 0:46:47,460
还有许多珊瑚礁生物在产卵
so do many other residents of the reef.

317
0:46:53,020 --> 0:46:55,060
各种生物的后代
A whole range of young

318
0:46:55,340 --> 0:46:57,300
横扫大洋
are swept through the oceans,

319
0:46:57,950 --> 0:47:00,740
寻觅无人之地 落地生根
ready to settle on a vacant site,

320
0:47:01,060 --> 0:47:04,660
再现这个复杂的生物群落
and bring back into existence the complex community,

321
0:47:05,100 --> 0:47:07,140
珊瑚礁
that is a coral reef.

322
0:47:18,900 --> 0:47:22,820
我们或许不知道未来的海洋还剩什么
We may not know what the future hold for our seas,

323
0:47:25,980 --> 0:47:28,660
但珊瑚礁可以再生
but coral reefs can regenerate.

324
0:47:29,380 --> 0:47:31,980
只要珊瑚礁一息尚存
As long as some reefs survive,

325
0:47:33,540 --> 0:47:36,260
希望便不会破灭
some hope can remain.

326
0:48:04,940 --> 0:48:06,420
法属波利尼西亚
French Polynesia.

327
0:48:12,340 --> 0:48:16,180
这里距离最近的陆地四千多英里
Over 4,000 miles from the nearest major land mass.

328
0:48:18,420 --> 0:48:20,300
这里没有渔获压力
Protected from fishing pressures,

329
0:48:20,380 --> 0:48:24,580
或许是褐点石斑鱼唯一的乐园
it's home to perhaps the last great gathering of marbled groupers.

330
0:48:25,380 --> 0:48:26,540
我们终于到了
We're finally here.

331
0:48:27,660 --> 0:48:29,220
花了好几天的功夫
It's taken quite a few days.

332
0:48:29,660 --> 0:48:31,540
我们不能说出具体地点
We can't actually say where "here" is,

333
0:48:31,780 --> 0:48:35,380
我们答应要保密
because uh, we've been asked not to mention the exact spot,

334
0:48:35,500 --> 0:48:37,500
因为这里是保护区域
because it's a protected area.

335
0:48:38,860 --> 0:48:41,460
摄制团队的拍摄遇到了极大的挑战
The team face a huge filming challenge

336
0:48:42,500 --> 0:48:45,300
因为通常褐点石斑鱼每年只交配一次
as the groupers normally spawn just once a year,

337
0:48:45,460 --> 0:48:47,660
过程持续不到一小时
and it lasts less than an hour.

338
0:48:50,700 --> 0:48:53,930
摄制组的顾问是生物学家 伊冯 萨多维
The team's advisor is biologist, Yvonne Sadovy

339
0:48:53,950 --> 0:48:58,140
她研究鱼类的产卵活动已有30余年
who's been studying fish spawning aggregations for over 30 years.

340
0:48:59,580 --> 0:49:02,820
这里的自然状态与数千年前
Here, it is close to the situation it has been

341
0:49:02,940 --> 0:49:04,140
十分相近
for thousands of years.

342
0:49:04,300 --> 0:49:08,140
这里恐怕是我所知的
It's pretty much the only place on the planet that I'm aware of

343
0:49:08,460 --> 0:49:12,420
地球上唯一一处褐点石斑鱼集中产卵的地方
where these groupers come together in the numbers that we see here.

344
0:49:16,780 --> 0:49:18,420
我非常希望它们会出现
I really hope that they're there

345
0:49:18,500 --> 0:49:21,140
不然我们就得空手而归了
because if they're not, then we've come all this way for nothing.

346
0:49:22,590 --> 0:49:24,720
我们选的时间没错吧 丹尼斯
We've got our timing right, haven't we Denis?

347
0:49:25,380 --> 0:49:26,820
- 确定吗 - 确定
- Confident? - Yeah.

348
0:49:45,820 --> 0:49:47,420
它们不会让你失望的
They're not disappointed.

349
0:49:53,220 --> 0:49:56,860
丹尼斯拍摄褐点石斑鱼的产卵已经15年了
Denis has filmed groupers gathering here for 15 years

350
0:49:56,980 --> 0:49:58,860
他很了解它们的习性
and has got to know their behaviour.

351
0:50:13,180 --> 0:50:15,740
不只有石斑鱼聚集在这里
The grouper aren't the only ones to be gathering.

352
0:50:20,220 --> 0:50:22,820
这还有世界上密度最大的
It's the highest density of grey reef sharks

353
0:50:22,900 --> 0:50:24,340
黑尾真鲨群
anywhere on the planet.

354
0:50:29,540 --> 0:50:33,340
这就是珊瑚礁的原始状态
This is what a pristine reef should look like.

355
0:50:33,940 --> 0:50:35,300
有数不胜数的捕食者
Lots and lots of predators.

356
0:50:37,860 --> 0:50:41,020
既然褐点石斑鱼出现了 那现在的挑战就是
With the groupers here, now the challenge is predicting

357
0:50:41,100 --> 0:50:43,100
预测具体的产卵时间
exactly when they'll spawn.

358
0:50:46,100 --> 0:50:49,980
为了评估拍摄距离 伊冯回顾了当天的视频
To judge if they're close, Yvonne reviews the day's footage.

359
0:50:50,860 --> 0:50:53,220
就我们所见 雄鱼正在向雌鱼求爱
From what we've seen here, the male's courting the female.

360
0:50:53,540 --> 0:50:55,220
如果你能放慢播放速度
When you can slow these things down,

361
0:50:55,340 --> 0:50:57,700
就能看见一些细节
this is when you begin to see some of this detail.

362
0:50:57,980 --> 0:50:59,940
你猜什么时候会产卵 明天吗
If you were a betting woman would you bet on tomorrow?

363
0:51:00,060 --> 0:51:02,140
我猜是明天或者后天
I would say tomorrow or the next day.

364
0:51:02,340 --> 0:51:03,860
我觉得就是这几天了
I mean I think they're pretty close.

365
0:51:05,100 --> 0:51:09,380
只有六名潜水员 摄制组无法进行不间断的水下工作
With only six divers, the team can't stay underwater all the time.

366
0:51:09,780 --> 0:51:11,620
所以根据经验
So, based on experience,

367
0:51:11,700 --> 0:51:15,140
他们决定在满月潮汐更迭之时下水拍摄
they decide to dive on the full moon's changing tides,

368
0:51:15,300 --> 0:51:18,100
想着帮助协调褐点石斑鱼产卵
thought to help coordinate grouper spawning.

369
0:51:20,140 --> 0:51:23,580
但今年 最凶猛的潮汐变化发生在夜晚
But this year, the strongest tidal change is at night.

370
0:51:25,300 --> 0:51:28,140
我们刚准备好第一夜的潜水设备
We're just kitting up for the first night dive.

371
0:51:28,500 --> 0:51:31,540
白天鲨鱼在这片水域徘徊
During the day, we've been seeing sharks around this area, but we don't know

372
0:51:31,620 --> 0:51:33,060
但我们不清楚它们晚上会怎么行动
how they're going to react at night.

373
0:51:33,180 --> 0:51:34,000
你紧张吗
Are you nervous?

374
0:51:41,860 --> 0:51:43,860
礁鲨会在夜晚捕食
Reef sharks hunt at night,

375
0:51:44,020 --> 0:51:48,260
为了以防万一 潜水员穿了防鲨服 戴了头盔
so the divers wear chain-mail suits and helmets as a precaution.

376
0:51:52,300 --> 0:51:55,380
一 二 三 四
One, two, three, four.

377
0:52:02,980 --> 0:52:04,500
潜水员检查设备 检查设备
Divers comms check, comms check.

378
0:52:11,140 --> 0:52:12,580
听得很清楚
Receiving you loud and clear.

379
0:52:17,700 --> 0:52:20,780
褐点石斑鱼尚无产卵迹象 但暗处
No sign of groupers spawning, but in the dark,

380
0:52:20,860 --> 0:52:22,980
鲨鱼蠢蠢欲动
the shark's attitude has changed.

381
0:52:24,580 --> 0:52:25,660
它们在捕食
They're hunting.

382
0:52:27,580 --> 0:52:29,860
鲨鱼利用电感受器来猎食
Using electro-reception to hunt,

383
0:52:29,940 --> 0:52:35,300
他们能调谐到最微弱的电刺激 包括摄影机的
sharks are tuned to even the smallest electro stimulus including the cameras.

384
0:52:43,340 --> 0:52:44,740
洋流正在涌动
With the current building,

385
0:52:45,060 --> 0:52:49,300
现在是与水面失去联系的最坏时机
now is the worst possible time to lose contact with the surface.

386
0:52:52,020 --> 0:52:54,580
我们身处无人之境 也不知道水下的情况
We're in the middle of nowhere. We have no idea what's going on

387
0:52:54,660 --> 0:52:57,260
我们只能听到断断续续的信号
down there. All we can hear is broken communication.

388
0:53:12,460 --> 0:53:15,780
由于褐点石斑鱼没有产卵迹象 他们结束了潜水
With no sign of spawning, they end the dive.

389
0:53:46,740 --> 0:53:48,900
摄制团队决定养精蓄锐
The team decide to save their energy

390
0:53:48,980 --> 0:53:50,980
为下一次潮汐更迭做准备
for the next change of the tide.

391
0:54:00,220 --> 0:54:03,260
长夜初白 他们开始为期待已久的产卵活动
At dawn, they prepare for what they hope will be

392
0:54:03,340 --> 0:54:05,940
做万全准备
the spawning event they've all been waiting for.

393
0:54:19,860 --> 0:54:21,820
坏消息 我们依旧
Bad news, we still are...

394
0:54:22,220 --> 0:54:26,060
但仅仅20分钟 潜水员就浮上水面
But after just 20 minutes, the divers are back on the surface

395
0:54:26,300 --> 0:54:28,580
给摄制组带来了毁灭性的消息
with some devastating news for their crew.

396
0:54:33,820 --> 0:54:34,980
我们错过了
We missed it.

397
0:54:35,340 --> 0:54:37,220
它们可能昨晚产的卵
Maybe they spawned last night.

398
0:54:37,660 --> 0:54:39,980
天哪 我也不知道
I don't... Oh, God, I don't know.

399
0:54:43,540 --> 0:54:44,980
摄制组晚了一步
The team were too late.

400
0:54:50,740 --> 0:54:54,420
我猜我们错过了好几个小时
So my guess would be that we've missed spawning by a few hours.

401
0:54:54,740 --> 0:54:57,260
或许鱼群达到了临界数量
And possibly, it's that they just reached some

402
0:54:57,380 --> 0:54:59,180
或者是临界密度
kind of critical mass or critical density

403
0:54:59,260 --> 0:55:00,860
就提前产卵了
and spawned a little bit early.

404
0:55:11,100 --> 0:55:14,620
第二年 伊冯回到法属波利尼西亚
The following year, Yvonne returns to French Polynesia,

405
0:55:14,900 --> 0:55:17,340
希望能更深入了解褐点石斑鱼
hoping to learn more about the grouper.

406
0:55:24,060 --> 0:55:27,420
今年 劳伦 巴列斯塔和其经验丰富的组员
This year, Laurent Ballesta and his experienced crew,

407
0:55:27,500 --> 0:55:28,980
接受了这项挑战
take on the challenge.

408
0:55:31,540 --> 0:55:34,100
由于潜水员人手充沛 他们有了新的办法
With many more divers, they have a new approach

409
0:55:34,300 --> 0:55:38,500
他们计划让劳伦在水里持续不断地监控
and they plan to have Laurent on watch in the water constantly.

410
0:56:01,460 --> 0:56:05,820
今年 经过数百小时的连续监控
And this year, after hundreds of hours of continual monitoring,

411
0:56:06,140 --> 0:56:10,420
他们终于成功捕捉到这项奇观的关键画面
they have captured the defining moment of this astonishing event -

412
0:56:12,060 --> 0:56:14,340
褐点石斑鱼产卵
the mass spawning of the grouper.

413
0:56:17,140 --> 0:56:20,060
我们有幸亲眼目睹
We have the privilege to be able to watch this process

414
0:56:20,940 --> 0:56:24,340
产卵过程 真的很令人激动
actually occurring. Uh, and that's a real thrill.

415
0:56:24,820 --> 0:56:27,580
它们对动物生物学有重大影响
They're really important for the biology of the animals.

416
0:56:44,140 --> 0:56:47,420
感谢两队专业人士的共同合作
Thanks to a combined team effort from both crews

417
0:56:47,540 --> 0:56:49,780
以及伊冯多年来的研究
and Yvonne's research over many years,

418
0:56:49,980 --> 0:56:53,940
我们终于能向世人诉说 褐点石斑鱼神奇的产卵故事
we could at last, tell the marbled groupers' incredible story.

419
0:57:02,340 --> 0:57:06,180
下一集 我们将去领略开阔海域的广阔无垠
Next time, we head into the vastness of the open ocean.

420
0:57:09,100 --> 0:57:13,020
为了在这片蓝色的荒芜生存下去 有的动物靠速度
To survive in this blue wilderness, some are fast,

421
0:57:13,860 --> 0:57:16,100
有的靠致命的谋略
others use deadly strategies,

422
0:57:17,420 --> 0:57:21,300
有的则依靠家庭成员间的亲密合作
and a few rely on the closeness of their families.

423
